My grandmother, our sweet #Grangela, has passed on. 🕊️ My family and I appreciate all the love you shared, and thank you for your thoughts, prayers and condolences at this time.

You were there for me from my first breath …
I was there for you until your last. 

The grief comes in such unexpected waves, but I am walking through it, grateful for the time we had. And appreciative for the endless love. ❤️💔 #Grangela 

Thank you all for your condolences. Spending time with family now, and reflecting on the beautiful memories. I’ll communicate more soon xo Shangie

Preparing to celebrate the life and endless love of my #Grangela, this Saturday, Feb. 18 at 2pm in Paris. 

Gram loved beautiful plants and flowers. If you would like to show your condolence in this way, delivery orders can easily be placed locally with PARIS FLORIST, located at 2549 Lamar Ave, Paris Tx / 903-784-6629. Link in bio. They will deliver to funeral home or service. 

Outside orders can be sent to MAXEY FUNERAL HOME (643 3rd St / 903-784-4032) no later than Friday evening, for Fannie Pierce or “Grangela”. 

Thank you again for allowing me and my family time to grieve her passing, while we also prepare a ceremony that honors the love she shared. May God bless you all. ❤️

Moments like this I’ll cherish forever. ❤️

… I don’t mean to overshare, or disrupt your day with this post … but y’all brought my #Grangela a lot of joy in her later years with your comments, your messages … your prayers in her times of challenge. So it feels right that, even though I’m feeling very heavy right now, we still continue to celebrate her together and embrace each other once more in this chapter of farewell. Gram was a golden lady with the sweetest smile … with her in my corner, I always knew I had someone praying for me, purely cheering me on. And what a blessing that she was around my entire life … to witness the journey that she helped shape, and be a part of so many of the cool moments. 

My family and I thank you for welcoming her into your life, and loving her the way you did. Send a prayer of comfort into the sky today as we say our goodbyes. 🙏🏽❤️

Rest well sweet Angel 🕊️ 
I’m forever grateful.

social_posts.post_text: I’ll forever honor Miss Tina Turner, and hold close the memory created the night she passed. I found out about her passing last week just before going into the Pink Dinner awards event in Puerto Vallarta. I was feeling very heavy emotionally - it’s been a pretty emotional first half of the year. But I quickly began to find reasons to smile. My Mom was there beside me (her first trip to beautiful Mexico), my dance pro and pal @glebsavchenkoofficial was there as we were both being recognized by the PV Pride Board for our journey on @dancingwiththestars, plus so many friendly faces who I soon realized were  most all Tina fans! So we bonded that night, and closed out the evening celebrating Tina … the talented @debbyholiday hitting the notes, and us joyously remembering the love that Tina shared with all the world. I’m grateful for these moments. And I’m grateful I can share them with y’all 💕🙏🏽

Hey y’all. IMPORTANT. Read this post below. I’m joining my friend @yvettenoelschure in her search for justice for her beautiful friend JONTY who was brutally and senselessly murdered this year in Grenada. Being the great example of kindness and generosity that he is, @tylerperry has joined Yvette and Jonty’s mother/family in the search as well and is offering an award. Read his post below.
. . .

Repost from @tylerperry … A few days ago I got an extremely heartbreaking phone call from my friend, Yvette Noel-Schure. Through her tears and grief she was telling me that in her home country of Grenada, a young man that was like a son to her was murdered. My soul ached as she shared that he was a young, gifted singer who was murdered because he was gay. My mind immediately went to Mathew Shepard, and all the other victims of racist, homophobic, antisemitic, xenophobic, senseless violence. This kid was 23, how is this ok? His mother is devastated. This pain is too common - the same pain of Marcia Williams, who I've been trying to help to find out what happened to her son Terrance in Collier County, Florida for ears now. The pain of not knowing can be crippling. It's the pain that my sister and I carry not knowing what truly happened to my 25-year-old nephew, who we were told hung himself in prison just 3 years ago. The pain of not knowing is truly gut-wrenching. So with that said, Yvette and I are offering a $100,000 dollar reward to anyone who brings forth information that leads to the conviction of the murderer of Josiah "Jonty" Robinson. Please pray for his mother and Yvette and all of those that loved him, as well as every family who has been impacted by senseless violence.

Posting this lil throwback to #TorontoPride 🌈 In honor of  Oct 11 - National Coming Out Day! On this day in 2019, I had just officiated 4 LGBTQ+ weddings in the @skittles Hall of Rainbows … and was en route to the stage for a performance. But seeing all the gay joy and freedom … the faces of fans who were so happy and bravely sharing who they were and who they loved with the world … I couldn’t help but stop and take in the moment. This video brings me happiness (and even tears) to this day. Not everyone in the world has this type of Freedom to be gay or even be a gay ally … as a host of @werehere I partnered with a lot of people in their own backyards that had a rough journey to acceptance. I had my own rocky journey too. But listen to me … no matter where u are, or who accepts u … you can start by loving and accepting YOURSELF. And when you know it’s your moment to embrace all of YOU, there is a community of love out here for u boo. 🏳️‍🌈 So to those who might be afraid or questioning, to those have “come out” and those who stand with those who do … I love all y’all … as I’ve learned to love myself. 💖 and I appreciate the luv in return xo

I love my Mommy. I’m Proud of my Mom. I see her trying. I see the effort. We both sometimes fall short of our health goals, but the important thing is to never give up. Never feel like you’ve gone so far that you can’t come back. Because you can. My mom is a Type II diabetic which is why I’m always nagging her “did u take ur meds? Did u exercise today? Have you been drinking enough water?” I know she’s the parent, but sometimes we have to parent each other. My mom was a live-in caregiver for Grangela, and now I’m encouraging her to make herself and her health the priority. And she’s doing the work. I’m sorry I nag, Mom. But I care. The way I know u care about me, and continue to push me forward when I stall ❤️ Here’s some encouragement for all y’all as we move toward 2024. If we can do it, and not give up .. y’all can too! Love u guys! Xo

And now nearly 60 years later, we are still fighting for fairness in voting and equality across the board. But don’t be discouraged … BE IGNITED!
